06273nam a22008415i 9781400826889DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008268897 a10.1515/97814008268892doi  a(DE-B1597)446408  a(OCoLC)979631815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC599.U5bA494 2005 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a323/.097322200aAmerican Exceptionalism and Human Rights /ced. by Michael Ignatieff.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b1 table.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction: American Exceptionalism and Human Rights -- tPart I. The Varieties of Exceptionalism -- tChapter 2. The Exceptional First Amendment -- tChapter 3. Capital Punishment and American Exceptionalism -- tChapter 4. Why Does the American Constitution Lack Social and Economic Guarantees? -- tChapter 5. America's Jekyll-and-Hyde Exceptionalism -- tPart II. Explaining Exceptionalism -- tChapter 6. The Paradox of U.S. Human Rights Policy -- tChapter 7. American Exceptionalism, Popular Sovereignty, and the Rule of Law -- tPart III. Evaluating Exceptionalism -- tChapter 8. American Exceptionalism: The New Version -- tChapter 9. Integrity-Anxiety? -- tChapter 10. A Brave New Judicial World -- tChapter 11. American Exceptionalism, Exemptionalism, and Global Governance -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the 2003 invasion and subsequent occupation of Iraq, the most controversial question in world politics fast became whether the United States stands within the order of international law or outside it. Does America still play by the rules it helped create? American Exceptionalism and Human Rights addresses this question as it applies to U.S. behavior in relation to international human rights. With essays by eleven leading experts in such fields as international relations and international law, it seeks to show and explain how America's approach to human rights differs from that of most other Western nations. In his introduction, Michael Ignatieff identifies three main types of exceptionalism: exemptionalism (supporting treaties as long as Americans are exempt from them); double standards (criticizing "others for not heeding the findings of international human rights bodies, but ignoring what these bodies say of the United States); and legal isolationism (the tendency of American judges to ignore other jurisdictions). The contributors use Ignatieff's essay as a jumping-off point to discuss specific types of exceptionalism--America's approach to capital punishment and to free speech, for example--or to explore the social, cultural, and institutional roots of exceptionalism. These essays--most of which appear in print here for the first time, and all of which have been revised or updated since being presented in a year-long lecture series on American exceptionalism at Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School of Government--are by Stanley Hoffmann, Paul Kahn, Harold Koh, Frank Michelman, Andrew Moravcsik, John Ruggie, Frederick Schauer, Anne-Marie Slaughter, Carol Steiker, and Cass Sunstein.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aExceptionalismzUnited States. 0aHuman rightszUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aNational characteristics, AmericanvCongresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aHoffmann, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHongju Koh, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIgnatieff, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb